repo_description: The theme chosen for our work has been the current one on the coronavirus or covid-19. This virus has entered the lives of all people on the planet for a few months, causing its lethality to stop normal activities of all kinds (jobs, routines...). Currently, this is a recurring topic and about which information is available almost 24 hours a day, due to its notoriety and magnitude. Regarding the chosen sources, the official website of the Spanish government and the Worldometers website have been selected as statistical sources. Both websites provide updated data on the virus, the first in Spain and the second worldwide. In this way, they are considered reliable sources because, in the first, the government is the one that would provide the data; and the second because, after carrying out an investigation process, it has been seen that the data they use corresponds to that of the corresponding governments. In addition, we have used Twitter as a textual source, a social network in which data can be collected more easily and, above all, immediately, necessary to establish temporal correlations between the evolution of the virus and society's opinion of it. This platform allows users to send short plain text messages, with a maximum of 280 characters. These messages, called tweets, are displayed on the user's home page and can be captured through an API provided by the social network itself.
